message.content:
The start symbol is

S → NT16 NT4

Hence whatever NT4 produces must form the very end of any string in the language.

The only rules for NT4 are  

NT4 → 't1'  (length 1)  
NT4 → NT15 NT0 (length 2)

where  

NT15 → 't8'  
NT0   → 't5' | 't8'

Therefore the only possible suffixes that NT4 can generate are  

• t1  
• t8 t5  
• t8 t8

The string we are checking ends with  

… t9 t5

None of the admissible NT4 suffixes matches the actual suffix (neither t1 nor t8 t5 nor t8 t8 equals t9 t5). Consequently no derivation from S can produce the given string.

Hence the string is not in the language.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT16 NT4  

Therefore the rightmost part of any sentence derived from the grammar is produced by NT4.

The non-terminal NT4 can expand only in the following ways  
1. NT4 → 't1'                                 (single terminal)  
2. NT4 → NT15 NT0                            (two or more terminals)

Case 1: If NT4 → 't1', the entire sentence must end with the single terminal t1.  
The given string ends with t2, so this case is impossible.

Case 2: If NT4 → NT15 NT0, the first symbol yielded by NT4 is whatever NT15 produces, and the last symbol is the last symbol produced by NT0.

• NT15 has only one terminal production: NT15 → 't8'.  
  Hence every derivation using this case begins with t8.

• NT0 has the productions  
  NT0 → 't5' | 't8' | NT24 NT25  
  If NT0 → 't5' or 't8', the last symbol produced is t5 or t8 (never t2).  
  If NT0 → NT24 NT25, the last symbol is produced by NT25.

  NT25 can generate  
  't9', 't8', 't4', 't0', or NT10 NT34.  
  If the expansion goes to terminals, the last symbol is never t2.  
  In the remaining possibility NT10 NT34, the last symbol is produced by NT34, whose terminal productions are  
  't8', 't1', 't0', 't5'.  
  Again, t2 is impossible.

Hence, regardless of how NT4 is expanded, the last terminal symbol it can yield is in {t1, t5, t8, t9, t4, t0}.  
The required last token t2 can never be produced.

Consequently the grammar cannot generate the given string.

No

The start symbol S must derive as
S → NT16 NT4

NT4 has only two possible forms
1. NT4 → 't1'          (a single terminal)
2. NT4 → NT15 NT0      (NT15 followed by NT0)

Therefore the string produced by NT4 is either
• exactly one token t1, or
• a sequence produced by NT15 (which can only be the single token t8) immediately followed by a sequence produced by NT0.

NT0, in turn, can produce at most two terminals:
• NT0 → 't5'
• NT0 → 't8'
• NT0 → NT24 NT25, where NT24 and NT25 each produce exactly one terminal (NT24 can be t5, t6, or t3; NT25 can be t9, t8, t4, or t0).

Hence every possible string produced by NT4 must be one of:

length 1:  t1
length 2:  t8 t5   or   t8 t8
length 3:  t8 (t5|t6|t3) (t9|t8|t4|t0)

All of these alternatives end with either t5, t8, t4, t0, or t9, but—crucially—the final two tokens can never be the pair t0 t5 in that order.

The given 30-token string ends with “… t0 t5”.  
Since NT4 is forced to generate the suffix of the complete string, and NT4 can never produce a suffix ending in t0 t5, the start symbol S cannot generate the provided string.

Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S expands as

S → NT16 NT4

so the first token of any generated string must come from NT16.

The only grammar rules for NT16 are
1. NT16 → NT30 NT31
2. NT16 → NT32 NT20
3. NT16 → 't0'

Because the given string begins with t2 (not t0), rule 3 is impossible, so NT16 must use rule 1 or 2.

t2 appears in the grammar only in the single production

NT30 → 't2'

Hence the first token t2 can be produced only by NT30 → 't2'.

Examine both possibilities for NT16:

A. NT16 → NT30 NT31  
   The sequence of terminals it produces starts with the token(s) from NT30 and is followed by those from NT31.  
   NT30 → 't2' supplies the first token t2.  
   The first terminal that NT31 can produce is always t5:
   • NT31 → 't5' (immediate), or  
   • NT31 → NT26 NT6, but NT26 itself begins with another NT31, and the recursion eventually ends with the base case NT31 → 't5'.  
   Therefore the second token generated by alternative A must be t5, contradicting the required second token t9.

B. NT16 → NT32 NT20  
   NT32 has only two productions:  
   • NT32 → 't0'  (would make the first token t0, not t2)  
   • NT32 → NT30 NT5  
      Here NT30 → 't2' again gives the first token t2, but the next tokens come from NT5.  
      NT5 can start with t3 (NT5 → 't3'), t1 (NT5 → 't1'), t8 (NT5 → NT15 …), or t7 (NT5 → NT18 …).  
      It can never start with t9.  
   Thus alternative B also cannot yield the prefix t2 t9.

Since neither possible derivation for NT16 can produce the required first two tokens t2 t9, NT16—and therefore S—cannot generate the given string.

Consequently, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT16 NT4  

Thus the generated string must be the concatenation of two blocks: the prefix produced by NT16 followed by the suffix produced by NT4.

The only ways NT4 can produce terminals are

1. NT4 → 't1'                                   (1 token)

2. NT4 → NT15 NT0 where  
   NT15 → 't8'                                   (first token ‘t8’)  
   NT0  →  
        a) 't5' or 't8'                          (1 additional token)  
        b) NT24 NT25 → (t5|t6|t3)(t9|t8|t4|t0)   (2 additional tokens)

Hence every string produced by NT4 must begin with ‘t8’ (except for the single–token variant ‘t1’) and its total length is 1, 2, or 3 tokens.  
Consequently, any sentence generated by the grammar must end with one of the following suffixes:

• t1  
• t8 t5 , t8 t8  
• t8 t5 (t9|t8|t4|t0)  
• t8 t6 (t9|t8|t4|t0)  
• t8 t3 (t9|t8|t4|t0)

The given string ends with the three-token sequence

… t6 t7 t4

This ending matches none of the possible NT4 suffixes (it neither starts with ‘t8’ nor equals the single token ‘t1’). Therefore the required decomposition S → NT16 NT4 is impossible, and the grammar cannot produce the supplied string.

No
